[normal]This follows the 
[normal]Soft Systems Thinking 
[normal]tradition started by 
[normal]Peter Checkland
[normal] 
[normal](Checkland, 2000)
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The hypotheses underlying the Systems Thinking Approach to Safety are as under:
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Release of harmful energy is a prior co
[normal]ndition
[normal]/state
[normal] to any 
[normal]physical 
[normal]event involving harm
[normal] 
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Lack of 
[normal]protective 
[normal]measures to 
[normal]mitigate the harmful energy so released leads
[normal] to injuries, loss
[normal] of limbs and lives
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Managerial oversights and assumed risk 
[normal](acceptable
[normal] 
[normal]risks are
[normal] risks accepted by an authority after a formal risk 
[normal]assessment)
[normal] are 
[normal]fallible decisions that trigger t
[normal]he accidental flow of events. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The single factor behind the lack of availability of safety measures to guard against the release of hazardous energy is
[normal] the 
[normal]systematic errors committed (
[normal]inherent biases
[normal])
[normal] in safety evaluations and risk assessments. 
[normal]Therefore, 
[normal]the 
[normal]utility of Systems Thinking Approach to Safety lies in screening out of hazardous scenarios from the concept of operations itself such that either the activity itself can be modified or specification of the infrastructure and control systems
[normal] may be written in a such way that probability of hazardous scenarios can be eliminated or controlled to the extent that it is no longer a cause for concern. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Objections against the utility of Systems Thinking Approach to Safety by the adherents of tradit
[normal]ional probabilisti
[normal]c and/or statistical 
[normal]approach to risk management 
[normal]are answered in t
[normal]his way. T
[normal]raditional method of estimatin
[normal]g numerically the risk 
[normal]posed by
[normal] an activity using the data collected from past accidents and 
[normal]by treating accident
[normal] fatalities 
[normal]as a ra
[normal]ndom variable does not yield insight into whether 
[normal]the activity is itself is safe or not due to availability 
[normal]and representative 
[normal]biases (pp137)
[normal] 
[normal](Kahneman, 2011)
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Traditional d
[normal]ecision making process entails making choices for th
[normal]e future to solve a given problem with various constraints impinging upon the solution. Both in theory and practise, 
[normal]utilitarian 
[normal]decision making entails a view to be taken of prevalent state of affair(s)
[normal] and partition them into risk less and risky choices 
[normal]. 
[normal]This representation takes the shape of an event tree diagram and probabilities are worked out against each outcome used in probabilistic risk assessment used by risk assessor and managers. The details of probabilistic risk assessment and its inadequacy t
[normal]o deal with human error were discussed by James Reason and therefore, not discussed again (pp219)
[normal] 
[normal](Reason, 1990)
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Prospect theory advanced by Nobel Laureate Daniel Kahneman and his collab
[normal]orator, Amos Tversky, highlights error
[normal]s in
[normal] the traditional utilitarian decision making and suggest the idea that emotions of hope and fear colour the 
[normal]choices we make when we want 
[normal]confront the problem of decis
[normal]ion making under risk. 
[normal]Thus, drawing lessons from the Prospect 
[normal]Theory
[normal] 
[normal]and his own 2010
[normal] publication 
[normal]author arrives at the judgement that long standing debate on morality and economics of safety can be concluded in favour of morality. 
[normal]Author’s 2010 publication argued that 
[normal]Group-think bias
[normal] is major factor in decision makin
[normal]g when setting safet
[normal]y standards was
[normal] noted by 
[normal] 
[normal](Appicharla, 2010)
[normal]. 
