[normal]Using 
[normal]the Bayesian Rules of conditional probabilities, we 
[normal]can
[normal] work out the probabilities of human actors’ performance 
[normal] 
[normal](Pal &amp; Sarkar, 2005)
[normal]. 
[normal]Total 
[normal]number of collision events 
[normal]reported 
[normal]in 2009= 3409. For risk computational purposes, it is assumed that there are 10,000 hours per annum. 
[normal]Let 
[normal]P (
[normal]B) den
[normal]ote the total probability of interactions between road vehicle and cyclists. 
[normal]The base rate of injurious collisions 
[normal]events 
[normal]per year 
[normal]suffered by cyclists
[normal]= P (A) = 3409/10000= 0.3409
[normal]The base r
[normal]ate of non –fatal non- injurious interaction events 
[normal]per year = P (A
[normal]C
[normal]) = 1-0.3409= 0.6591
[normal]The probabi
[normal]lity of a fatality given a colli
[normal]sion situation = P (B/A) = 13/3409= .00381
[normal]The probability of an 
[normal]injury given a colli
[normal]sion situation = P (B
[normal]C
[normal]/A) = 3396/3409=0.99619.
