[normal]James 
[normal]Reason (1990) argued that problem solvers tend to over simply causality (pp91)
[normal] 
[normal](Reason, 1990)
[normal]. Causal explanations suffer from various kinds of biases. 
[normal]Author has noted the fact Nobel Laureate Bertrand Russell’s 
[normal]perceptual 
[normal]acco
[normal]unt o
[normal]f everyday world
[normal] of seeing, hearing, touching, smelling and tasting subs
[normal]tances is an illusion. 
[normal]Bertrand Russell may be echoing the ancient statement of Epicharamus that it is the mind that sees and hears; all besides is deaf and blind is stated by Art
[normal]hur Schopenhauer
[normal] 
[normal](Schopenhaeur, 1813/2006)
[normal].  
[normal]According to Arthur Schopenhauer, to order to contemplate an explanation for a particular thing, one must assume that there is subject (oneself) that thinks about the object 
[normal](to
[normal] be e
[normal]xplained)
[normal]. However, in the cases of explaining a sequence of events that led to an accidental death, we must be carefully to avoid repeating errors committed by David Hume and Immanuel Kant in their causal explanations. David Hume asserts that all conseque
[normal]nce is mere sequence of perceptions whereas Kant affirms that all sequence of perceptions must necessarily be consequence. The law of causality is not known to us empirically but is given a priory (pp 106
[normal]/107
[normal])
[normal] 
[normal](Schopenhaeur, 1813/20
[normal]06)
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]O
[normal]verthrowing of causality 
[normal]as suggested by Bertrand Russell 
[normal]following the sceptical philosophy of David Hume is
[normal] not a remedy 
[normal]in the hope that science has absorbed all philosophy
[normal] 
[normal](Russell, 1945)
[normal], 
[normal](Rasmussen, et al., 1994)
[normal].  This 
[normal]idea 
[normal]is 
[normal]evidenced from the writings 
[normal]of Nobel
[normal] Laureate Albert Einstein, author of relativity theories
[normal],
[normal] who 
[normal]urged us to consider
[normal] the role of causal reasoning in scientific 
[normal]explanations
[normal]. An 
[normal]illustration of causal reasoning 
[normal]stated 
[normal]by Albert Einstein 
[normal]is given. B
[normal]y means of comparison of steam arising from water boiling in a pan heated on a gas stove 
[normal]with a steam not arising from the adjacent pan 
[normal]not lit
[normal], Albert Einstein argued that heat is the c
[normal]ause for the effect of steam arising
[normal] from the pan
[normal](
[normal]pp
[normal]72)
[normal] 
[normal](Einstein, 1920)
[normal]. 
