[normal]From the partial HAZOP study it can be inferred that accelerating motorised traffic relative to cyclist is an occupational hazard. 
[normal]Because in a relative (from Albert 
[normal]Einstein’s perspective)
[normal] 
[normal]universe, 
[normal]inertial path is less than accelerated path
[normal] or in
[normal] geometric terms, the diagonal of a triangle is less than 
[normal]sum of it sides is shown by Sir Roger Penrose
[normal] 
[normal](Penrose, 2004)
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Having established the fact that the Traffic Light System can induce errors and contribute a collision h
[normal]azard, it is necessary to pay attention to the barriers that can prevent and protect the cyclist from this occupation hazard. 
[normal]Pedestrians are also killed due to error in the specification of traffic light systems. 
[normal]A road user may be presented with a green 
[normal]aspect and motorised traffic with a flashing amber aspect thus giving rise to an opportunity for an accelerating motor traffic   to collide with a pedestrian. This aspect is usually ignored by safety researchers. For
[normal] example
[normal], a study of Transport for Lond
[normal]on on Pedestrian Safety completely ignored 
[normal]role of traffic lights and focused on behavioural aspects and measures to remedy the behaviour. 
