[normal]This section describes in general the concept of system approach to safety. 
[normal]This section introduced to draw a clear distinction between system approach to safety and system approach to 
[normal]safety assurance
[normal]. Both of these methods are described in freely available online publication
[normal] 
[normal](Appicharla, 2012)
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal](A.G.Hessami, 2012)
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The third information item
[normal] on page 
[normal]3
[normal] may be surprising to 
[normal]an 
[normal]unfamiliar reader
[normal]. 
[normal] However, those who are conversant with the works of Dr Ashby work on Cybernetics know that information conveyed by a traffic light with a cycle
[normal] symbol display contains a variety of messages
[normal] 
[normal](Ashby, 1957)
[normal].  The meanings assigned to the elements of the set of messages Red, Amber, and Green such as Stop, Caution and Go may appear unambiguous to the reader but physically these messages introduce ambiguity. There are cyclic transitions between aspects from Red
[normal] to Red-Yellow, Yellow to Green and Green-Yellow –Red to command stopped traffic to move and command a flowing traffic to a halt. Out of probable nine states (lit, unlit and failed state and ignoring the transitions pointed out earlier) only five are utili
[normal]sed by the road user to infer. In other words, a fraction of 5/8= .625 fraction of the probable states 
[normal]from user perspective 
[normal]is useful. Thus, the quantity of information used by a user of the traffic light system is only 62.5% and the rest 37.5% are don’t 
[normal]care situations. Apart from this, the specification of the twin traffic lights systems assumes a mathematical Cartesian Framework of Co-ordinate system in infrastructure planning and delivery:  the eastbound cyclist has an early start and therefore will no
[normal]t be in conflict with the left turning vehicles. 
[normal]It is hard to imagine the role of non-Euclidean frameworks of Geometry in daily modern work life.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Reactions to the Bow Roundabout accident by various stakeholders reported in the general press varied depe
[normal]nding upon their roles: cyclist
[normal], lorry driver, commissioner of transport or CEO of a charitable organisation
[normal], and the Mayor of London. Cyclist Commissioner,
[normal] 
[normal]Andrew Gilligan, took a  
[normal]pessimistic view that designing out hazards is not feasible
[normal] 
[normal](BBC News, 2013)
[normal]. The Mayor of London, Boris Johnson, as a knee jerk reaction promised to invest one billion UK pounds of funds over next ten years to improve safety of the cyclists and appears to be sharing the same view advanced by
[normal] 
[normal]An
[normal]drew Gilligan by admitting the idea that no traffic engineer in the world can imagine every eventuality that can occur on the road
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Author does not consider the proposition of how person A can harm person B unintentionally at a road junction cannot be i
[normal]magined by a group of traffic engineers, given the past history of such occurrences. However, author considers it is realistic to consider the idea that traffic engineers may be impaired in their ability to plan for safety improvements without giving rise 
[normal]to unintended effects.  Because they may be under cognitive stress to balance safety risk concerns against a legal and cost decision criterion and thus
[normal],
[normal] may be biased in their approach to hazards management. 
[normal]Author notes that Nobel Laureate Daniel Kahnema
[normal]n argued successfully that there is no such thing as cost efficient risk management criteria when moral intuitions are taken into account
[normal] 
[normal](Kahneman, 2011)
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Safety and the avoidance of risk 
[normal]are major concerns in any 
[normal]engineering
[normal] activity
[normal].
[normal] For more details on various interpretations of the word, risk, readers may wish to consult the paper hosted on the Stanford University Website
[normal] 
[normal](Hansson, 2011)
[normal]. There is an extensive discussion on 
[normal]the epist
[normal]emological understanding and deﬁnition of risk
[normal] in a paper published by 
[normal]Catherine E. Althaus
[normal] in 2005
[normal] 
[normal](Althaus, 2005)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Catherine E. Althaus
[normal] argued in her 2005 paper that 
[normal]story of history about
[normal] risk may be dating back 3102 BCE
[normal] and
[normal] other ancient civilisations
[normal]. 
[normal]From a hindsight perspective, author infers that the 
[normal]chanting of peace mantras by the sages of the Upanishads indicates awareness of concept of harm 
[normal]and peace on their part 
[normal]dating back to 3000 BCE as per some historians
[normal] of ancient India
[normal] 
[normal](Valerie, 2003)
[normal]. 
[normal]Thus, author does not feel that there are 
[normal]any 
[normal]novel ideas about risk assessment and
[normal] 
[normal]management
[normal] 
[normal]of sources of harm (hazards) 
[normal]in this submission. 
[normal]  
[normal]From a human error (Swiss Cheese Model) pers
[normal]pective, active errors are errors whose effects are felt immediately and latent errors are whose effects lay dormant for a time period
[normal]. Human error experts acknowledge the idea that Management Oversight ad Risk Tree is a technique that can be used for org
[normal]anisational analysis and safety studies in the published literature and on Wikipedia database
[normal] 
[normal](Rasmussen, et al., 1994)
[normal].  
[normal]Based upon the reading of the foregoing philosophical and psychological papers  author is of the
[normal] professional opinion that every accident can be prevented: blaming the active human errors on the part of the cyclist and/or truck driver involved in the accident, and/or defending the latent human error on the part of traffic engineer and managers, and/o
[normal]r entertaining the naïve hope of raising awareness on the part of the cyclist or the heavy vehicle (lorry or bus driver) through technology, and/or accepting the theological position that such events are all acts of God 
[normal] 
[normal]is no solution to the problem faced
[normal] by the cyclist. Because cyclist accidental death arises from known physical, situational and cognitive factors and these factors may be managed through application of right resources: prioritising safety is absolutely necessary when using information cont
[normal]rol systems via modern technology that can unintentionally release harmful energy. An instance where these facts go recognised familiar to the author is drawn from the railway transport domain. Besides author, German academic aviation researchers and DB ra
[normal]ilways are not convinced of the ability of the new European automatic train control system, ETCS, in averting hypothetical collisions between trains
[normal] 
[normal](Appicharla, 2013)
[normal]. An IEEE paper published by Armin Zimmermann and G
[normal]unter Ho
[normal]mmel
[normal] of Technical Berlin University in 2003 observed that probability of trains braking under GSM-R radio based automatic train control system operating in moving block system is 94% for the time deadline of 6 seconds, braking distance of 4500 metres, leng
[normal]th of 410 metres. The probability worsens with increase of time deadline and braking distance
[normal]. Thus, positive safety performance of ETCS can be regarded as doubtful. Further, this conviction finds support in the case of metro train control system failures
[normal] as well. The cancellation of Bombardier’s Signalling Contract by Transport for London is 
[normal]a 
[normal]evidence
[normal] in support of the assertion made
[normal]. 
[normal]Despite the contrary and relevant evidence from three sources, the European Railway Agency and GB Railway Industry orga
[normal]nisations consider promoting the European Train Control System (ETCS) as a 
[normal]satisficing
[normal] strategy. 
[normal]Developing a common safety regulating strategy to promote ETCS as a standard automatic train control system is the main focus of managerial attention at this
[normal] point of time. Author agrees to the idea that German aviation
[normal] and DB railway 
[normal]researchers were right in drawing their readers’ attention to the inherent weakness in the ETCS technology. But German aviation researchers have not considered the contribution o
[normal]f latent human errors in the specification of the TCAS device in 2002 accident prior to thinking about the solution to the problem of rail and/or road accident situations
[normal].  Apart from the sources cited, author 
[normal]has 
[normal]learnt that practitioners in the safety critical railway domain suffer from lack of awareness of Systems Thinking Approach to Safety as well. This inference is drawn from reading Ali Hessami’s work on safety assurance approach 
[normal](A.G.
[normal]Hessami, 2012)
[normal]. Ali Hessami is the main author of the Yellow Book and CENELEC railway specific safety standards used by Network Rail, ORR, RSSB, ATOC and Transport for London Railway Organisations for safety assurance.  Ali Hessami follows the traditi
[normal]onal methods of safety assurance assuming the equation user error equals human error. In his previous role of Head of System Safety, Ali Hessami promoted the Yellow Book for Engineering Safety Management methods. 
[normal]The utility of application of Yellow Book t
[normal]ype or fault and event tree modelling process for supporting safety critical decisions is learnt from the example as these procedures cannot be used for modelling fallible decisions that shape the performance of operators or users of electrical/programmabl
[normal]e/ software electronic control systems. 
[normal]James Reason (1990) observed that failure types that originate at the management layers and take the shape of fallible decisions and finding ways to neutralising these the major challenge facing human factor researc
[normal]hers with preserving the safety of complex, high risk systems. This Submission has shown how the fallible decisions
[normal] when implemented that pose danger to 
[normal]a cyclist
[normal] 
[normal]from a particular example of Bow Roundabout Accident 
[normal]can be revealed 
[normal]without conducting 
[normal]deep 
[normal]mathematical and 
[normal]psychological research. 
[normal]Author has noted that risk can be approached in several ways and has made efforts to include all the perspectives into the accident modelling and analysis. 
